# CS499 Capstone
### Eportfolio Self Assessment

Throughout the development of my Course Planner application, I demonstrated a clear progression in both my technical skills and my understanding of software engineering best practices. The original implementation successfully met functional requirements by utilizing a binary search tree (BST) to store and retrieve course data efficiently. However, as I revisited and enhanced the project, I focused on improving performance, maintainability, scalability, and overall code quality.

In my first round of enhancements, I improved the structure and usability of the application by introducing stronger input validation, duplicate detection, and better user feedback. I refactored the code to separate responsibilities more clearly, such as introducing a dedicated file-loading class, which improved modularity and readability. I also implemented additional functionality, including course counting and more consistent input normalization, which made the application more robust and user-friendly. These changes reflect my growing understanding of clean code principles and the importance of designing software with both the user and future maintainers in mind.

In the second enhancement, I made more advanced improvements focused on performance optimization and memory safety. I eliminated redundant traversals in the BST insertion process, reducing unnecessary computational overhead. Additionally, I replaced raw pointers with smart pointers (`unique_ptr`), significantly improving memory management and eliminating the risk of memory leaks. I also strengthened string parsing and normalization, ensuring consistent and predictable behavior across all user inputs and file data. These changes demonstrate my ability to apply modern C++ practices and optimize data structures for efficiency and reliability.

The final enhancement represents a significant step toward building a more complete and production-ready system. I extended the application beyond static data processing by adding persistent storage capabilities, including saving updated course data back to a file. I also implemented dynamic in-memory update operations, such as adding new courses, modifying course titles, and managing prerequisites. These features required careful consideration of data integrity, input validation, and user interaction design. Additionally, I ensured deterministic output and improved data consistency by normalizing and validating all stored information.

Overall, this iterative development process highlights my ability to critically evaluate my own work and continuously improve it through structured enhancements. I demonstrated growth in key areas including algorithm efficiency, memory management, modular design, and user-focused functionality. More importantly, I developed a stronger understanding of how to evolve a simple academic project into a more scalable and maintainable software solution.

